  "duration": 69.94,
  "text": "This is where stoichiometry gets powerful. You can predict exactly how much product you'll make from any amount of reactant. Here's a real question. How many grams of carbon dioxide form? When you burn 12 grams of carbon, step one, write the balanced equation. C plus O, two, arrow, CO, two, already balanced. One carbon, two oxygens each side. Step two, convert to moles. 12 grams of carbon divided by molar mass, 12 equals one mole. Step three, use the mole ratio. The equation says one mole of C makes one mole of CO2. So we need one mole of CO2. Step four, convert back to grams. One mole of CO2 times molar. Mass 44 equals 44 grams. That's it. 12 grams of carbon makes 44 grams of CO2 every time. The pattern is always the same. Grams to moles use the ratio, moles back to grams, grams, moles, ratio, moles, grams. Memorize that flow, and you can solve any reacting mass question.",
